column13: Now that I'm aware that, on the first purchase, ChargePoint charges an additional $5.00 to your credit card, I decided to add $2.25, or so (out of $2.75 credit).  After all, why should they be allowed to keep more of my money than they already are?  But, when I pulled up to the first charging station, it took me several minutes to get to the point on the app to, Start Charging. :-(  Once I got it hooked up, and going, all was going OK. Yay!  But, after a few seconds, I noticed a, Not Charging, message. :-(  So, rather than fight that station again, I moved my car to the next one.  And, finally! Got this station working, and added, $2.29 (about 12 miles) to my EV.  Now, to be honest, these public charging stations are great while traveling. However, depending on the state, regular gas vehicles can be cheaper to fill up.  But, for driving around town, and despite the long time needed to charge on a 110V outlet (12 hours gave me 45 miles. The cost? $0.84! Yes, only eightyfour cents!).  So, for gasoline/diesel vs home electric costs, EVs are a much better deal. Though, still cost prohibitive for many people (starting at around $38,000, and can exceed $250,000).  But, prices are dropping (just like the first Plasma 40" set was $14,999.99). And, in a few years, EV prices are expected to be under $30K for the lower end models  My EV recommends leaving it plugged in. But, because I live in an open Duplex community, I don't want to risk someone stealing my charger.

column13: This has worked for me a few times and is in a good location, but out of the many charging stations I‚Äôve used, I like the Webasto / AV network by far the least (which is what is at this location). The app PlugShare has been a lifesaver for finding alternatives and is very user friendly. The chargepoint charger by tofurkey hq is a much better option.  The phone call required to start up Webasto stations as a non-member tends to take a full 10 minutes every time - other brands‚Äô stations (blink, chargepoint, Volta) do not require a call to start, so having to call and wait on hold seems like a pretty unnecessary hassle.  Webasto are also the only brand of chargers that has been unreliable for me - today, this charger did not work, and I had one instance elsewhere where the charger inexplicably timed out. In both cases, calling customer service to troubleshoot was pretty frustrating - today, the rep insisted the problem was my car and not the station, even though 2 other brands of stations had worked for me in the past day. Immediately after our call I drove to a chargepoint station which worked successfully, so I followed up and informed Webasto that the problem was indeed their charger, not my car.  I am hoping Webasto addresses this issue - this location is so convenient and I‚Äôd love to charge here. Based on my experience and frustrations with the company though, I‚Äôll be charging elsewhere when available - have never had any reliability or customer service issues with other companies.

The next morning I found that the driver's side window of my car had been VANDALIZED by a tesla employee/representative.  Clearly, these parking spaces are being leased by tesla from the hotel, so tesla is exerting its property rights. That's fine, tesla, but HOW ABOUT POSTING A SIGN WARNING THAT YOU WILL BE VANDALIZING MY CAR IF I PARK IN YOUR PRECIOUS SPACE? Really lousy corporate citizenship; but who among us is surprised by this behavior from tesla? You'd think that a company with so much expensive equipment sitting un-monitored at thousands of locations around the country would be careful about promoting vandalism. Yes, I parked in your precious parking space, tesla; but you went completely Putinesque with your response.  To be more precise: those parking spaces are not parking spaces: they are charging spaces. Even a tesla owner may not park there for FIVE MINUTES after the conclusion of charging, or tesla will start billing their account a trespassing fee. I cannot make this stuff up: go to their website for confirmation. Now, on top of having my car vandalized by this corporate miscreant, I feel the need to count myself fortunate that i was not also charged a trespassing fee.  In Teslaworld, there are two kinds of customer: tesla owners; and The Enemy. And even tesla owners must remain on their best behavior, or face punishment. I can only imagine that the rest of the tesla customer relationship must be quite self-affirming for low self-esteem Masochists.  You need not trouble yourself, tesla, with the concern of ever having my business in the future.

column13: We visited the casino and buffet on a concert night. We had to stand in line for the buffet to wait for tables to open up. They had a sign up explaining they were short staffed like so many other places, which I understand.  There was one long table with Reserved signs on it that nobody ever sat at - I am thinking that was probably related to short staffing and trying to keep up. I don't eat meat so I asked if I could order the kids grilled cheese and fries, which they were nice enough to let me. I was actually surprised how fast my meal came considering, and it was hot and fresh. My husband had the buffet for $25 because he has always been about quantity over quality.  When he left food on his plate and only made two trips through,  you know it's BAD! He said the selection was way down from when he has been there in previous years. He said the food was just gross. He admitted my idea of picking up pizza in Mandan would have been much better.  We did wander around the casino area for a little while before and after the concert.  The layout is not crowd friendly, as there are so many machines jam packed in there that you add a few people and there is not much room to move.  I thought the concert hall was extremely warm, and I am the one that is always cold, so it had to have been bad! Our seats were right under a light on the side wall, which glared in our eyes and made it hard to watch people coming and going while we waited for the concert to begin.

Then you have to go unplug and plug back in to start a new session. The NEMA 14-50 and NEMA 5-20 (120v) outlets are still there if you have your UMC on you. column13: I've used this many times with my Model Y. I'd give it 5 stars except for: A: It's up a long, steep mountain road, so it'll eat a lot of juice just getting here from Winthrop. B: The resort has a strict No Dogs policy, so we never stay there. Great place for hiking in the summer, and XC skiing in the winter. Great views.My Wife and I drove our Telsa Model Y over for a weekend stay and had good luck with the charging station provided by Sun Mountain Lodge. There are two Tesla level 2 chargers and one non-Tesla - the Tesla chargers that we used operated at 48A at 208V. We left our car charging several times while eating at one of the restaurants or out hiking. We were able to add enough range to drive around for the weekend and to make it back home in Bothell without having to stop.This is the only Tesla charging available in hundred miles radius and it didn't work for me during the Labor Day weekend (2020). I left supercharger at Burlington, WA with full charge (280 miles worth), Winthrop is 140 miles one-way, so it was a tight roundtrip with no room for error; so I visited this destination charger hoping to add 30 miles for safety. Neither of the 2 Tesla chargers worked (the charging port glowed red, and the panel said 'charging equipment fault'). The faculty at the lodge tried to reset the chargers a couple of times, but that didn't change anything.  First, the destination chargers are at the top of a mountain that's 12 miles from Winthrop, but takes 25 miles worth of battery to reach from Winthrop -- so, when you go there and the charger doesn't work, you've now wasted 25-30 miles of battery to make that trip up the hill and in vain. No one at the lodge can tell you either upfront if the chargers work or otherwise -- they won't know.  There's a third non-Tesla charger; but beware it's a 30A charger, which will charge about 17miles per hour at best.  I suggest - don't bother with this charging option unless you have a 10kWh buffer to gamble with. Instead, your best bets are some of the camping grounds (KOA for example) that lets you use 50A plugs for 5-6 hours in RV camping slots for $20 or so (of course you'd need your charging cable & adapters). In fact, the entire SR-20 stretch is a terrible idea with a Tesla right now -- until Tesla installs a supercharger in Winthrop. Hope they do soon -- it's one of the popular routes for camping/vacationing.

column13: I wanted to provide an update on this charging station, as some of the details have changed from other reviews.  This station does charge for power, scanning the QR code at the power source prompts you to add the app and add a credit card for payment.  This station is not fast-- it took about 4 hours to fully charge our battery from 50%, but much faster than plugging into a 110 wall outlet.  It is in a great location, and we happily spent those hours shopping, eating and wandering around the plaza.Avoid at all costs. I brought my Tesla here due to some high winds about a week ago. It took me and my husband 50 minutes to even get the charging started. When we did get it started, it charged at 7mi/hr, which is about the same as a standard wall outlet.  The mobile app, neither iOS nor Android, worked at all. It just errored out with no option. We spent the majority of the time trying and trying again the browser app to get to payment without timing out. The site itself seems to have been created in Italy where the creators assume you are located. The app didn‚Äôt work at all unless the charger was plugged in, however the instructions state differently.  If you absolutely need to use this one, here is what you should do. 1. Start with the charger plugged into your car. Scan the CR code on the charger. 2. Follow the prompts but make sure you adjust your address from Italy to US. Also make sure you use your billing address for the credit card you plan to use. The site will take about 30 seconds to load each step. 3. There are several screens where you will need to enter your information. 4. You will need to attempt this process several times because if you get a timeout message throughout any of the steps, you will have to start over from scratch. Trying to get back to where you were will be fruitless. 5. Finally, at the end, you will get a message warning you that the car is not plugged in and you have 60 seconds to do so. The car should already be plugged in and beginning to charge. Do not remove the charger from the car or you will have to start at the beginning. column13: Ready for vacationers and locals!  I was worried it wasn't in service with the UI in our vehicle stating it was operating at reduced service.  So far I've used two different chargers and they both worked as expected.  This station is so new that it doesn't even have labels yet as of September 5th, 2020.  6 stalls. I'm assuming it's going to be A and B stalls adjacent to each other (like the newer stations have).  Update (7/Sept/2020): 2nd charger from right keeps malfunctioning when trying to latch. All others are in working order as of this update.Supercharger near Ocean City Maryland on Rt. US 50 just before the bridge into Ocean City. It's conveniently located at a Royal Farms. As you can see from the pictures, at first the electrons were flowing very fast. When I had only sixty miles of charge, the battery was accepting nearly 500 miles of range per hour of charge. If only it had stayed like that, but no. It didn't.  As the amount of charge increased, the rate of charge decreased. I'm told that this is what happens at all supercharging stations. By the time I got to 80%, my rate of charge dropped to 146 miles of range per hour of charge. By the time I was closing in on 90%, my rate of charge was around 100 miles of range per hour of charge. Clearly, the best strategy for long trips is to keep the battery below 80% because recharging above that takes a long time. This works only if charging stations are very close to the route and reasonably close to each other.  Another trip to O.C. Different charge stall than before. Still works the same way. column13: April. 26.2022(Fast charging  station actual visit used day)  We were visiting Austin for my husband's medical appointment at VA Clinic. EV map was showing Most fast charging stations  located near by downtown and Round Rock.  Me and my husband from west central Texas(lil over 3hrs away from Austin),and we wasn't sure where to find a fast charging station for our 2020 Kia Niro EV.  Luckily, we found this spot but EV map wasn't showing a whole lot a details. Whether it has CHAdeMO, CCS.and J1772.  Soon as we were at this location,  OMG , I see the FAST charging station and nobody wasn't using at the time. There is  only 2 fast charging tower and 1 of tower wasn't available.  Luckily next to other charging tower was work.  We used CCS charger.  Before we put on charger, we only had a 39% power left on our car. We put on charger about less than 40 minutes later, it was 90% full.  This is just reminder,  with CCS charger battery wont charging a 100%. I do not know why they capped at 90% but, yeah 90% is  max capped. It wont let you charging any further. So if you want to charge your battery for 100%, you have to switch to CHAdeMO for rest of 10%.  0.21 cents per kw, yeah, it was little higher than where my husband went to last time. (Last time he went to Walmart EV charging station and their rate was 0.12 cents per kw. And this was only about 3 or 4 month ago). I guess because it located at right by airport  that maybe the reason why its pricey on this charging station.  Oh also,  at this location,  they have WHATABURGER, Subway, TEXACO gas station,  and few other convenient shop at same shopping center.  I just hope they have more than 2 CCS and CHAdeMO fast charging station.One station has painters tape on it saying it doesn't accept payment so we tried the other one.  It wouldn't initiate with the Chargepoint app so we tried with Apple pay.  That worked but it wanted me to acknowledge that I wasn't using a membership and the touch screen doesn't work well so I had to randomly press around on the screen until I luckily got it to register that I accepted the fact that I was just paying with a credit cardWhoever put this station in Rocks!  Next door to airport parking lots and a coffee shop.  Great for that little bit of power you need to get home.Great place to wait when you are picking up and you are right there at the terminals. Very nice and clean inside if you need food or drink. Can buy gas while waiting.  Its the best of both worlds.  Too bad other airports don't have a brain to do this.  Oh and you dont have to pay just to come and drop off or pick up. The days of DFW Airport are gone. It is totally worth the drive if you are even a little closer to that ridiculous DFW. No tolls to get here and no pay every time you have to drop off someone and go back to pick up. You can buy a meal for what you have to pay to get to and in DFW. Bergstrom International hands down an awesome airport. Im thrilled we are 24 minutes closer but I would go to Bergstrom if it was further wayCool little place to charge your electric cars, before a long trip after an airport ride, pick up a couple of snacks at the corner store, or the joining Whataburger.

column13: The chargers are in the parking garage on the P2 level, which is paid public parking (see photo for pricing) mixed with resident parking for the Waycroft apartments. Residents and visitors are notorious for leaving their vehicles (electric or otherwise) idling in these charging spots overnight, so don't rely on the "available chargers" data from Google. LAZ Parking leaves warnings on these vehicles, but doesn't appear to be towing them.  When entering the garage, don't enter the first gates you see; instead, follow signs for Resident Parking / Vehicle Return to find the P2 gate. After entering the P2 gate, turn left, following the sign for Resident Parking. As mentioned before, P2 is resident parking AND paid public parking. P3 is strictly for residents only, and is gated separately.  Chargers are marked by green parking spaces. There are 3 of them to your right as soon as you enter P2, and 4 more near the Waycroft elevators further back.  Remember to lock your vehicle. I've heard of multiple thefts in this garage, and have personally caught a thief on camera on the P2 level in the wee hours of the morning stealing from unlocked vehicles. I wouldn't leave my car plugged in here overnight unless there aren't any other options.Have to pay for charging and garage parking. column9: 930 Kinnear Rd, Columbus, OH 43212, USA
column13: The fast charger was working. We used it to bring my Nissan leaf from 18% up to 81%. One word of caution. OSU has disabled the stop button on the charger and the one in the app also does not work. You have to use your cell phone or Chargepoint card to reauthorize in order to stop the charger. This caused some frantic moments before I discovered this. The fast charger will not unlock the charge cable from the car without a stop command. I would advise OSU to add some signage explaining this to people using their charger.As the sole winner of the U.S. Department of Transportation‚Äôs (USDOT) Smart Cities Challenge, Columbus was awarded more than funding and designation as America‚Äôs Smart City; but more importantly the coveted job of a global teacher for cities around the world on how to ‚Äúbecome Smart‚Äù by embracing the reinvention of transportation to accelerate human progress. Columbus received a total of $50 million in the form of two grants, $40 million from USDOT and $10 million from Vulcan, Inc., a Paul Allen company. These dollars provide the seed funding for Smart Columbus, a region-wide Smart City initiative co-led by the City of Columbus and Columbus Partnership.  The City of Columbus, under the leadership of Mayor Andrew J. Ginther, is the lead recipient of the $50 million and will administer the deployment of these funds for the duration of the grant period, which concludes at the end of 2020.  The Columbus Partnership, representing the Columbus Region‚Äôs private sector, is the lead implementation partner for the grant program and is responsible for the initiative‚Äôs Acceleration Fund, which is credited as a significant factor in Columbus‚Äô winning of the challenge. The Acceleration Fund, which started out as $90 million now totals more than $360 million and is composed of coordinated and aligned investments by the private and public sector to compliment, scale, and sustain Smart Columbus projects and programs.

column13: ChargePoint has it over all the others IMHO. column9: 274 SW 4th St, Madras, OR 97741, USA
column13: All four high speed charging stations were available and working. I am so thankful for this ChargePoint location. It made access to Central Oregon possible from the Portland area.  From here you are able to progress south to Bend or North back through Hood River and points beyond.Excellent chargers in a perfect location. Really appreciate the very clear indication on each charger that it's available--easily readable before parking. (With other chargers--particularly Electrify America--you don't find out one is unavailable until you've already pulled into a spot.) The Black Bear diner is just across the road for dining-in or take-out while charging. The only thing that could be improved is the short charge cable--a bit difficult to reach the Chevy Bolt charge port.Rates are high. Almost 30 cents per kw. You must have an account to use the charger. My charge point charge card rarely works first time to start the charge. The worst part is... When you are done charging and want to quit you CANNOT press the Done button on screen. This seems to be specific to the chargers run by Pacific Power. The protective screen is so thick it doesn't register finger presses. So either you need to stop charging in the app or call the 1800 number. Which by the way, the 1800 number isn't printed on the machine. There is also no stop charging button on the machines either besides the untouchable touch screen. So over all the charge point stations run by Pacific Power suck.The first reliable 50kW DCFC east of the Cascades! A definite stop enroute to Bend for any Chevy Bolt driver coming from Portland!Never so happy to use this charger. We arrived with only 1 mile left on our 2022 Mustang Mach E . The charger was fast and after a quick dinner @ BlackBear Diner across the street, we were on our way.

The protective screen is so thick it doesn't register finger presses. So either you need to stop charging in the app or call the 1800 number. Which by the way, the 1800 number isn't printed on the machine. There is also no stop charging button on the machines either besides the untouchable touch screen. So over all the charge point stations run by Pacific Power suck.The first reliable 50kW DCFC east of the Cascades! A definite stop enroute to Bend for any Chevy Bolt driver coming from Portland!Never so happy to use this charger. We arrived with only 1 mile left on our 2022 Mustang Mach E . The charger was fast and after a quick dinner @ BlackBear Diner across the street, we were on our way.

column13: Charging is no longer free, and there may be a 'parking fee' as high as $0.20/min that kicks in during the day.This charger is very nice and convenient. The chargers are sponsored by the Village of Marble Cliff and are free to use.  The brand is ChargePoint, which has an App for your smartphone that can be used to start the charging process. If your phone has Near Field Communications enabled it can be used like a RFID card to get the charging station started if the ChargePoint App is installed and running. The only caveat to this location is the designated parking spots are a little unwieldy for charging a Nissan Leaf with the front charge ports. column13: Small detour from I5. Close to a lot of food places. (Starbucks, taco stand). Can use restroom in Starbucks or any other food place.  There is also a decent sit down restaurant called Taste of India.  Lots of parking space if you want to move your car after charging.Horrible supercharger. Always full and even at 20% SOC, I get 47 kW and 1 hr to 80% charge. The only good thing is the Starbucks nearby. If you need amenities, I suggest you get your coffee and bathroom break here and then proceed to the Gen 3 supercharger in Buttonwillow 11 miles down the I5 (24551 West Lerdo Highway). It is not on Google maps yet but it is on Tesla‚Äôs map. There are no amenities at the Gen 3 charger (seems like they are building a center but it is not completed) but you get charged in half the time.Great BBQ place across the street. Fresh slaw and quality food. Surprised to get such a good sandwich so fast while I was charging. Quick at the counter. Hard to see it from the street, but right behind the big EZ sign.About 10 chargers here, right next to Starbucks so you can get some coffee and use the rest room. There are a bunch of gas stations around here too if you need to buy something.Conveniently located off the highway for easy access. Only fast food options available. Doesn't seem to be a very busy location though.

column13: The one compatible charger was halfway through an installation process and would require an installer to finish setting it up. And the app did not work right to report the problem.This was our first time using Charge point and we had a bit of trouble using the system.  The customer service agent was very helpful and walked us through the method.  Once we got everything set up properly it went fine.  Other comments I have:. It was 108 in Red Bluff. The charge rate is listed as 62.5kilowatts, but it charged at 32 and took much longer than expected.OK location, but only charges 30 kW if there are two cars charging....3x 48kw CCS/Chademo L3 DC chargers, multiple L2 and Tesla destination chargers and friendly air conditioned Best Western lobby9/24/22 three charges all seemed to be working. column13: Saved by a Chargepoint J1772 charging station in Weed, CA!  Returning from a Seattle Thanksgiving roadtrip, we didn‚Äôt have enough battery to reach the 16 stall Supercharger at Mt Shasta. column13: Groups of 50kW DC Rapid Chargers. Each with 3 connectors: Tesla, CHaDemO, & CCS-Combo.   Price: $.30/per Min-which on a 50kW charger, is anywhere between $.41-.70 per kWh (which is what other networks use to calculate price-energy consumed, rather than time spent & therefore usually cheaper). Though they do power 100% of their electricity from Renewable Energy, via buyback programs with sustainable energy farms. Still pretty expensive‚Ä¶but with Electricity already being drastically cheaper than gas, I don‚Äôt mind contributing to a green cause if it means I get awesome parking upfront, more space & security around my car. But since 20-30min is more than enough for a DC Rapid charge unless low on battery, I‚Äôd prefer a cheaper AC Level 2 option, similar to other EvGo stations.  *Note: As of 2021, about 51% of CA Electricity already comes from Renewable/Emissions-Free Energy.Charge rate not as fast as Tesla supercharger, but quite decent.  The only thing is the Tesla cable is too short. So if the middle parking is being used, you can‚Äôt charge your Tesla on any of the other two on the right or left.

column9: 2901 Spirit of Texas Dr, Austin, TX 78719, USA
column13: April. 26.2022(Fast charging  station actual visit used day)  We were visiting Austin for my husband's medical appointment at VA Clinic. EV map was showing Most fast charging stations  located near by downtown and Round Rock.  Me and my husband from west central Texas(lil over 3hrs away from Austin),and we wasn't sure where to find a fast charging station for our 2020 Kia Niro EV.  Luckily, we found this spot but EV map wasn't showing a whole lot a details. Whether it has CHAdeMO, CCS.and J1772.  Soon as we were at this location,  OMG , I see the FAST charging station and nobody wasn't using at the time. There is  only 2 fast charging tower and 1 of tower wasn't available.  Luckily next to other charging tower was work.  We used CCS charger.  Before we put on charger, we only had a 39% power left on our car. We put on charger about less than 40 minutes later, it was 90% full.  This is just reminder,  with CCS charger battery wont charging a 100%. I do not know why they capped at 90% but, yeah 90% is  max capped. It wont let you charging any further. So if you want to charge your battery for 100%, you have to switch to CHAdeMO for rest of 10%.  0.21 cents per kw, yeah, it was little higher than where my husband went to last time. (Last time he went to Walmart EV charging station and their rate was 0.12 cents per kw. And this was only about 3 or 4 month ago). I guess because it located at right by airport  that maybe the reason why its pricey on this charging station.  Oh also,  at this location,  they have WHATABURGER, Subway, TEXACO gas station,  and few other convenient shop at same shopping center.  I just hope they have more than 2 CCS and CHAdeMO fast charging station.One station has painters tape on it saying it doesn't accept payment so we tried the other one.  It wouldn't initiate with the Chargepoint app so we tried with Apple pay.  That worked but it wanted me to acknowledge that I wasn't using a membership and the touch screen doesn't work well so I had to randomly press around on the screen until I luckily got it to register that I accepted the fact that I was just paying with a credit cardWhoever put this station in Rocks!  Next door to airport parking lots and a coffee shop.  Great for that little bit of power you need to get home.Great place to wait when you are picking up and you are right there at the terminals. Very nice and clean inside if you need food or drink. Can buy gas while waiting.  Its the best of both worlds.  Too bad other airports don't have a brain to do this.  Oh and you dont have to pay just to come and drop off or pick up. The days of DFW Airport are gone. It is totally worth the drive if you are even a little closer to that ridiculous DFW. No tolls to get here and no pay every time you have to drop off someone and go back to pick up. You can buy a meal for what you have to pay to get to and in DFW. Bergstrom International hands down an awesome airport. Im thrilled we are 24 minutes closer but I would go to Bergstrom if it was further wayCool little place to charge your electric cars, before a long trip after an airport ride, pick up a couple of snacks at the corner store, or the joining Whataburger.

column9: 2478 N Columbia St, Milledgeville, GA 31061, USA
column13: ALERT! Be aware that, not only does ChargePoint charges an additional $5.00 on your credit card on the first purchase (my bill was $22.75 (01:29:00 + 00:01:00 idle time to disconnect ;-(  ) CP made 2 charges; 1 for $10 00 + 1 for $20.00), but depending on the state, they can bill either by the kWh used. Or, by the minute (much more expensive).  Now that I'm aware of CP charging an additional $5.00, I decided to add $2.25, or so (out of $2.75 credit).  After all, why should they be allowed to keep more of my money than they already are?  But, when I pulled up to the first charging station, it took me several minutes to get to the point on the app to, Start Charging. :-(  Once I got it hooked up, and going, all was going OK. Yay!  But, after a few seconds, I noticed a, Not Charging, message. :-(  So, rather than fight that station again, I moved my car to the next one.  And, finally! Got this station working, and added, $2.29 (about 12 miles) to the my EV.  Now, to be honest, these public charging stations are great while traveling. However, depending on the state, regular gas vehicles can be cheaper to fill up.  But, for driving around town, and despite the long time needed to charge on a 110V outlet (12 hours gave me 45 miles. The cost? $0.84! Yes, only eightyfour cents!).  So, for gas vs home electric costs, EVs are a much better deal. Though, still cost prohibitive for many people (starting at around $38,000, and can exceed $250,000).  But, prices are dropping (just like the first Plasma 40" set was $14,999.99). And, in a few years, EV prices are expected to be under $30K for the lower end models  My EV recommends leaving it plugged in. But, because I live in an open Duplex community, I don't want to risk someone stealing my charger.

column9: 1200 E Washington St, Hayti, MO 63851, USA
column13: The two fast charging stations are very slow at times. I only was able to charge at 28Kw when I can always fast charge at 55-75Kw rate at other stations. One station said it was available and would not charge my car. Ameren and Chargepoint need to get their act together and make these stations fast and reliable!Out of all the chargepoint DC chargers I've used. This one has always worked even if it took 5 min to start once. That said, there are messages about reliability issues on Plug share for this station.  Nearby Fazolis and Schnucks gives you something to do while you charge. From a very low battery, I got ~150 miles of range in 15-20 minutes (only vehicle there). It shares a battery with the spot next to it, so it can be much slower (and typically is at the end of the charge).Always works ! Was able to charge at 82kw without any issue every time.  Great job ChargePoint:Charging between 71kW and 121kW, not too shabby!

I guess he was right, since mine stopped working after adding a mile or two and charged me $ 4.48. When I came back, I had to start the session over completely (broken screen) and was billed $ 21.45 the second time.  This took 1 Hour nd 25 minutes to add 183 miles, not what I call a fast charge.  Later in the day I stopped at a EA station and in 11 minutes had added 46 miles. That one was fast! No comment from the company when I called asking about the $ 4.48 charge for a broken charger. Next time I'll drive on to Forsyth and use the EA charger.Cp is the best, no issues fast charging and bam on your way!Customer service is awful and the station doesn't work so far in the entire state of Georgia none of the charged point stations have worked and none of the customer service people have done anything other than yell at us for information and want us to do their jobPerfect

column9: 134 High St, Buffalo, NY 14203, USA
column13: NOTE: THIS 134 High St/850 Michigan Ave parking garage is now a PRIVATE garage only for pass-holders of the Buffalo-General Medical Center and the Wyndham Garden Downtown Hotel (125 High St). So the 10 FREE ChargePoint level-2 chargers are in regular use for commuters, although as a hotel guest I got to use the charger to re-charge my Kona overnight (for the hotel valet parking charge of $18) because I arrived after 7pm, and all but one of the chargers were available.  The hotel's evening valet went with me let me into the garage to set up the charging session, and the morning valet went with me to let me drive out.  That morning when I checked out, the other 9 chargers were being used, and I was probably depriving some 8am arriving commuter of #6's use.

column13: Absolutely horrible experience. The charger only charges 10 miles per hour and it turns off when Kohl's isn't open so it stopped charging at 11pm. Big scam Kohl's!!  You are only doing it to be able to say you are supporting the environment when in reality you really don't care.  Putting in the equivalent of a dryer electrical connection would charge 3 times faster.  A regular electrical outlet in a house chargers at 5 miles per hour so this isn't much faster than that. column13: Excellent stop! Got to 250kW immediately, near great travel stop and hwy exit. Much better choice than the Davenport supercharger by all measures. Travel stop has food court with lots of indoor seating, noodles of snack and beverage options as well as souvenirs and a small I-80 'museum'. Clean and ample restrooms. Largest travel stop in the world gives you lots of room to walk around and explore if you want to stretch your legs. Highly recommend this supercharger.  Wendy's, Caribou coffee/Einstein bagels, DQ/orange Julius, Pizza Hut, Taco Bell inside and Arby's across the street.One of the first charging stations I've been to that has a trash can next to the chargers. There are also chargepoint chargers available. Close to the truck stop and truck museum with plenty to doFairly new location for Tesla, located within the Iowa 80 truckstop (Claims to be the largest truckstop in the world). Prices slightly higher per KW compared to other charging stations we utilized on our trip from Denver to DavenportVery nice place to stop by for charging - it has total of 8 Tesla connectors with max 250KWH power delivery (V3 super charger) for charging very quickly. It has multiple options for food like Pizza hut, Iowa 80 Kitchen, Dairy queen, Wendy's and for coffee lovers, there is a caribou coffee shop . Also the charging station is right next to the I80 truck museum- really worth visiting who likes or interested in knowing about the trucks. This place also has the charge point company connectors available for non Tesla electric vehicles.Great supercharger stop. Plenty of room to back into the chargers. Lots to do in the truck stop with a food court and shopping available.

column13: One of the lower rate superchargers along the corridor from Tahoe to Bay Area. There have been a few times when I had to wait, but not very long. With the other Folsom Supercharger offering more options for food and shopping, this one tends to be forgotten.The Supercharger delivers as expected, though it could have been better placed.  To reach the chargers, take the first left-turn into the parking lot from Iron Point Road and then turn right again to enter the parking lot. The four parking spaces are along edge of the lot near Iron Point Road, but roughly in the middle of the lot between the the first and second parking lot entrances.  The location could be better. There is no overhead cover against rain and sun, and nothing above eye-level to indicate where in the parking lot the chargers are located. There's no sidewalk nearby and the short charging cables mean you have to park nose-in and cannot pull through when leaving. The rightmost two parking spots are the most convenient - they back onto an aisle between rows of cars, while the two spots on the left are across from a curb and row of cars, which gives you less space to back out.  The Folsom Premium Outlets are convenient if you are traveling Highway 50, less so if you need to get back onto I-80. The outlet mall is extremely focused on clothing, so options for spending time there while charging during a road trip are limited. Most of the dining options are fast food and most are across Iron Point Road.I visit here a few times a month to charge up. There a few convenience shops and fast food chains in walking distance. At 9:30 they call and say it will be at least another hour.  Keep in mind it's January in Nebraksa and now rolling into evening. column13: This has been the most reliable Electrify America (EA) location that I've encountered.  Most EA locations utilize what I've come to think of as "plug and pray" technology because that's what EA customers find themselves doing. Praying that the charger is going to actually work.  Thankfully, I've visited this location on multiple road trips up into the Lassen National Forrest. I found that the chargers worked every time which is truly miraculous as any frequent EA customer knows. These appear to be updated charging units and I suspect this explains my good fortune.  Near by food and beverage amenities are abundant. Stoble's coffee is my fav. Lots of options within reasonable walking distance in a safe, small town, downtown district area.  My only complaint is that when this area is busy and the lot is full of ICE cars and EVs, EV drivers who must back into these angled stalls will have some difficulty (i.e. backing in without touching the Rivian in the stall to the right; or the Lucid Air in the stall to the left; or without ramming into bubba's truck nuts equipped tow hitch on the F-250 parked in the stall directly on the other side of the one way lane).  I wish EA wouldn't just cram these chargers into random, small sized parking lots with limited approach angles and limited maneuvering space. For real, when full, it is challenging to back in. Even worse, the cords are too short to reach the back of my teeny tiny Polestar 2 when pulling in nose first! If EA could at least give us longer cords at this location the issue I just described would be avoidable.New to charging an EV and this is a good location and seems safe in a bank parking lot. column13: Really nice to have this 25 charging station location in NYC. It is about a 10 to 15 minute drive from the BQE highway exit depending on traffic so you have to go a bit out of your way to get to the location. As of this review, all 25 chargers work with ccs1, 23 work with tesla, and 2 work with chademo.  You could pay with credit card, or tap with the revel app if you put in payment info within the app. Just be aware that that I was told by a Revel tesla taxi driver that sometimes the payment might not work at a station from time to time. This happened to me on my first visit. I could not get my payment to work. The driver suggested I try a different stall and that solved the problem. So if you have trouble paying to get the chargers started, try try again.  As of this review, the price of the charge is priced at 39 cents a kwh plus tax. Some of the chargers says 75 kwh max but my tesla only got just below 50 max and at times dip to the high 30s. I read that is common. Not sure if that is limited to tesla or most evs here.  I am really glad this place exists. Nyc really need more places like this to make evs work. Hope this survives and that they would expand to other locations in NYC.  I had to take out a star though because it would be nice to have a restroom for those long charge times if needed.I have been to this charger four times over the past two weeks. The chargers are supposed to push 75kw. They have never reported charging above 44kw. My Tesla Model Y has never reported charging above 36kw despite the meter saying it was charging at 44kw. There are lots of spaces but there are zero amenities (no bathroom, no food, sketchy bodega two blocks away). I am really excited for this location to improve (we need this!!!) but as of July 20 it‚Äôs barely operating. Don‚Äôt give up Revel, we need you!I read all of the bad reviews at this station and wanted to give it a try myself with the new Tesla brand CCS adapter because I read that Tesla‚Äôs could only get 50KW with the Tesla adapter that the charging station has.  I‚Äôm pleased to find out that with the CCS adapter I got 71KW at its peak and 56KW at its low point. It was a really cold day so it took my battery sometime to heat up but I would assume on a nicer day I could hit 70KW faster.  Just be aware that this station puts a pre charge of $30 on your credit statement and it adjusts to what you will actually be charged.Note, per the specs limit of the "Tesla CHAdeMO Adapter" that Revel uses to charge Teslas as this site, 50 kW is the fastest possible speed you'll see, but other brands should see faster speeds using the CCS connector.  This is an inclusive facility with the promise for much easier ownership of any EV brand that‚Äôs capable of DC fast charging, which is nearly every EV sold today. It should really help make EV ownership much more of a possibility for local residents of Brooklyn, without having to pay to get into a garage just to charge.  There were some payment processing issues experienced by several Teslas on the evening of July 7 2021, the very first day Revel launched their payment processing system at this site. Contactless payment (Apple Pay with non-Amex card such as Visa or Apple Card) seemed to work better than magnetic card swipes or chip reading. I have compiled a list of the variety of issues we saw, and reported them to Revel on July 8th 2021. Revel has stated that at least some of the known issues have been resolved.Brand new 2023 Ford Mustang Mach-e (extended battery) was showing 71.4kW+ when charging there for the first time, I wouldn't be surprised if it reached 75KW after it conditioned when I wasn't looking. column13: ALERT! Be aware that, not only does ChargePoint charges an additional $5.00 on your credit card on the first purchase (my bill was $22.75 (01:29:00 + 00:01:00 idle time to disconnect ;-(  ) CP made 2 charges; 1 for $10 00 + 1 for $20.00), but depending on the state, they can bill either by the kWh used. Or, by the minute (much more expensive).  Now that I'm aware of CP charging an additional $5.00, I decided to add $2.25, or so (out of $2.75 credit).  After all, why should they be allowed to keep more of my money than they already are?  But, when I pulled up to the first charging station, it took me several minutes to get to the point on the app to, Start Charging. :-(  Once I got it hooked up, and going, all was going OK. Yay!  But, after a few seconds, I noticed a, Not Charging, message. :-(  So, rather than fight that station again, I moved my car to the next one.  And, finally! Got this station working, and added, $2.29 (about 12 miles) to the my EV.  Now, to be honest, these public charging stations are great while traveling. However, depending on the state, regular gas vehicles can be cheaper to fill up.  But, for driving around town, and despite the long time needed to charge on a 110V outlet (12 hours gave me 45 miles. The cost? $0.84! Yes, only eightyfour cents!).  So, for gas vs home electric costs, EVs are a much better deal. Though, still cost prohibitive for many people (starting at around $38,000, and can exceed $250,000).  But, prices are dropping (just like the first Plasma 40" set was $14,999.99). And, in a few years, EV prices are expected to be under $30K for the lower end models  My EV recommends leaving it plugged in. But, because I live in an open Duplex community, I don't want to risk someone stealing my charger.

It's located between the McDonald's, Cold Stone Creamery, and Freddy's Custard.  There are 16 spots that charge up to 250kW.  I've come here several times and it's usually no more than 50-75% full and have always had fast, consistent charging speeds.  There's plenty of shops in the area to grab a bite, drink, or do some casual shopping.  Last few times I stopped by, the McDonald's interior dining area was closed, but there's several small eateries if you want to sit down or use the restroom.Usually pretty empty at nights but, conveniently right off 35. I think not. Avoid these stations if you can, absolute robbery! $1.99 connection fee and $.50 a minute! And after you plug in you realize they are all on reduced power (15-30 miles per hour of charge) too late, you just lost $2 to find that out. Even if they were at full power, (150-300 miles per hour) 300 miles at $.50/min is $30 plus the $2 connection fee. Leave it to a casino to rip us off. I fear more predatory station owners will try the same tactics to cash in on the EV boom.‚ÄúSecuring Power‚Äù was the message we got while trying to charge at station 3 - waited for 6 minutes and nothing changed. column9: 6024 U.S. 93 S, Whitefish, MT 59937, USA
column13: Where do we start‚Ä¶ Concrete blocks 2 feet off the curb make it just about impossible the use the chargers in the first place. Chargers say 125 or 100 kw/h shared, most we have been able to get is 28.4 kw/h.. Generally takes from 10-15 tries to work, often only get 5.4kw/h ‚ÄúFast Charge‚Äù. They charge per minute so it‚Äôs a great deal for them. Govt money was used from MT DEA for these and they are not within those guidelines, not even close. So the station owner took the money and ran as the saying goes. Only gave it a 1 star since there is no option for 0.All chargers offline. Called support to restart a fast charger multiple times only to get limited charging speeds, and charging stopped after less than a minute after support hung up.Updated 07/12/2022: The concrete blocks have been removed! Thanks for your responsiveness. Max charge is still 28kw but still far preferable to 6kw. Desperate for a charge and this was our only option. Max charge was 28kw. Short cable. The cement blocks in front of the charge units force parking a little too far for the cable length, and the height could really damage a vehicle. On the plus side, the Town Pump is a nice amenity with clean restrooms and plenty of food.The j1772 port worked well for an overnight/destination charge for my tesla. Concrete block was a bit weird but could still easily reach the charge port. I got a full 30amp at 208v, resulting in 24 mi/hr.Very new station with about 6 stalls. However only two plugs that work with the standard Tesla adapter.  4 x CHAdeMO / CCS/SAE stations that only work with a very particular adapter for Tesla that's difficult to get hold of. 2 stalls are J-1772 which work with Tesla but at a very slow charge rate which isn't useful given the location. All functional when I visited.

column13: A little far from 95 relative to other locations along the highway, but a good location at Sheetz which offers a fairly clean bathroom and decent drink and food selections.My new favorite I-95/US1 Supercharger stop in VA!  For years I'd hit the Sheetz for Food and the Glen Allen Supercharger for fuel, but now I don't have to. There are 8x v3 (250kW / "Superfast") charging stalls here at a renovated Sheetz. That means you can stuff your face with all the cheesy, fried, delicious MTO food you're used to while your ride gets a snack of its own. 9 times out of 10, if you order hot food your Tesla is charged enough to get to the next leg of your trip by the time you get it. And as always, the staff here is super friendly and gives you that awesome Sheetz service.  5/5 for clean toilets, a nice fresh renewed look, the new Dolewhip machine! and an easy to pull into charging location away from the crazy traffic of the gas pumps! Also, because the Sheetz is open 24 hours, if you get here late late late at night, you still have toilets available to you (unlike you do at strip mall locations--sorry Glen Allen!)  Tips: - Come here for superfast charging and delicious road food to take with you on your drive. - Head a few miles south for the Glen Allen Supercharger for sit-down restaurant service and charging at a more relaxed pace (that is less likely to get you overage charges). - Best place to evaluate traffic conditions and decide whether you want I-95/I-295 or US1 for the next leg.A little far from the interstate. But most importantly, WHAT A FEATURE FILLED STOP THIS IS. This shopping mall has a ton of food options available (including my go-to, award-winning, local pizza company, The Original NY Pizza). Not in the mood for fast tasty pizza? What about Thai? A Sports Pub? Chicken and Waffles?  Need a coffee or to kill 40 minutes while you charge? Stop into the excellent Meeples Brew, a friendly board-gaming cafe that will make the time zip on by.  Then of course there's the Bass Pro Shops. Nothing will make the charging time disappear like wandering the aisles thinking about what you can buy for your next hunting/fishing/camping trip. And they tend to keep pretty clean bathrooms as well.  There are two hotels nearby too, so you have a place to crash, or to ask to use the bathroom if you're stopping for a charge after 10PM.  12 out of 10 amps. column13: I recently had the pleasure of visiting the Tesla Supercharging station at Hotel Mission Del Oro, and it was nothing short of a delightful experience. The station's location is just perfect, as it's conveniently situated near the freeway, ensuring a quick and hassle-free pit stop for travelers.  Hotel Mission Del Oro itself is an exquisite property, offering top-notch amenities for those looking to unwind while their vehicle gets charged. The hotel's welcoming ambiance and well-appointed rooms provide a comfortable stay for guests. And if you're an AT&T user, you'll be pleased to know that the cell phone service is excellent in this area, making it easy to stay connected with friends, family, or work.  One of the highlights of this Supercharging station is its proximity to popular walkable dining options. My personal favorite has to be In-N-Out, which is just a short walk away. This iconic fast-food chain never disappoints with its mouthwatering burgers and shakes, making it an ideal choice to grab a quick bite while your Tesla charges. There are several other eateries in the vicinity, catering to a variety of tastes and preferences.  Adding to the convenience, the charging station is equipped with multiple Superchargers, ensuring availability and minimal wait times. The charging process itself is swift, allowing you to get back on the road in no time.  In conclusion, the Tesla Supercharging station at Hotel Mission Del Oro is an excellent pitstop for Tesla owners. column9: 100 Jaguar Land Rover Way, Mahwah, NJ 07495, USA
column13: For a traveler, there isn't anything else here, except a nice mountain view and the DCFC. The fast charge is great and there are plenty of fast chargers, as well as L2 chargers. No restroom. You'll want your car sunshades. For the employees of Jaguar Land, this must be fantastic. You can plug in a J1772 while you're at work. Or use the CCS or CHAdeMO for a quick "fill-up" anytime during the day.Thank you for creating this massive amount of chargers however what is up with the pricing structure?! I used the Level-3 Quick Charge (CCS/SAE Combo) for 5 minutes and only received 2kWh at 40¬¢ per minute!? That would be on the very high side per kWh which is what I thought it must surely be. Nope, per minute. I was charging an e-Golf and only charged at 24-25kW which is extremely low for a Level-3. Please be competitive with Electrify America, EVgo and other ChargePoint stations. I often pay zero, but this is extremely high. I didn't check the cost of the Level-2 as I was very low and didn't want to even entertain waiting here for a few hours. Please revise pricing per kWh and I'll gladly come back as well as update this review. I wound up charging at an Electrify America at the speed of around 50kW (still slow for level-3) at a very high 43¬¢ per kWh with no subscription.Great fast new chargers but ONLY for Jaguar employees.Great EV Charging, fast, it's in the jaguar range Rover parking lot, lots of chargers, plus slow chargers as well. Open to the public, no you do not need an account, you can just tap your credit card and start

column13: Not far off the freeway and located near a BP gas station / Arby's as well as Starbucks. Arrived with 1 of 8 chargers in use. Initial charge rate was 215kwh and dropped as the battery filled. Charged our M3 long range from 34% to 80% in 26 minutes.  Used again on 6/27/2022 about 11:15am.  Arrived with 0 of 8 chargers in use. Charged our M3LR from 25% to 85% in 26 minutes.Excellent location. Conveniently located right off an exit by a Starbucks and BP station. We did not go into the BP, but did walk in Starbucks. If you plan on getting anything there, I HIGHLY recommend putting in a mobile order ahead and walking in while you charge because this is a pretty busy area. Please revise pricing per kWh and I'll gladly come back as well as update this review. Much better experience than what I had in Raleigh.The stalls are new, the charge rate is fast, however it should not cost nearly 8 times as much as charging at home. column13: Very nice place to stop to get a charge. It‚Äôs one of the last stops coming from the bay area and going to the casino in Jackson. We actually didn‚Äôt charge all the way and still made it back to charge up to get back to the bay area. I hope they get the supercharger in that area because it‚Äôs still a little nerve wrecking!  But if you come during the day there is a bass pro shop a big mall and bathrooms to go to. They have security as well. If you come at night everything is and was closed for us but we are used to most things being closed when I supercharge at night. I still felt safe especially because I had the men with me and my mini!  Not sure how I feel I was alone but it‚Äôs very open plenty of time to observe and prepare. I will come here again.Charged the X here on a Thursday morning about 9am. Located to the side of Bass Pro Shops. Not busy in the parking lot, but there were 5 or 6 other Tesla's charging. Have learned a few Supercharger locations along the route from Las Vegas to Bay Area.  This is located on Perimeter Road in a Manteca shopping center on Hey 120, after turning off CA Hwy 99. Would recommend as a location to charge.

column13: Stopped here Aug 2022 for an almost desperate tesla charge but was disappointed. I don't have the right adapter for the fast charger which was $5. to connect. There are no chargers up and down 35 from the cities nor from here to WI along HWY 8.Stopped here on the way to and from northern Wisconsin. Both times the charger was in use when we arrived. Had to wait approximately 30 minutes for the fast charger. Used one of the 2nd level chargers while we waited for the fast charger to free up. There aren't a lot of other fast charging options nearby at the time of writing this (July 2021) so it's a popular spot. There is a pretty butterfly garden to look at, and there is a city park about a block away as well as a Casey's gas station within walking distance.We stopped here on July 3rd to add 15-20 minutes worth of charge time from the level 3 CCS charger to our 2020 Kona Ev ultimate so we could make it to Hayward, WI and then ultimately back to this charger to top off on our way home on July 4th. Likely due to the holiday weekend and sunny weather, we did encounter a shiny new fully electric Mustang charging when we arrived. There are ample level 2 J-1772 connectors here if you find the level 3 charger occupied. The level 2 chargers showed anywhere from 7.5 - 11KW in which was nice to add even a few miles to our battery while we waited for the Level 3 to open up. The mustang driver noticed we must've been waiting for the L3 charger and since they were just topping off while they had some time they cleared out and let us charge. Station worked great to quickly add some miles before we ventured to a friend's cabin in Hayward which is around 120 miles away.  We stopped again just to get enough miles to drop our friend off at home in Uptown Minneapolis and then make it home to our house in New Hope. "station at Commerce Bank - Maryland Heights - 12633 Dorsett Rd, Maryland Heights, MO. Your charge session has ended. column9: Mt Shasta, CA 96067, USA
column13: One dc fast charger.  Bathroom in the Ray's.Accessible, easy to operate (same as any other Chargepoint charger), with a little bit of shade nearby.The charging worked well this was our second time at a charge point station the first one was a disaster in Red bluff the problem with the charge point monolithic chargers is they are in black and if they are in the sun they are scalding hot the power cord is too hot to touch with your bare hand you need to have a oven glove or a rag or something to put this in however this one was in the shade so we locked out it worked very well again my main complaint was so-called fast charging stations and this may be my car they're too slow I charged it about 33 KW per hour

column9: 9310 Corporate Dr, Selma, TX 78154, USA
column13: This is the Mercedes dealership. The employees here are so nice and allowed me to charge my EV6. I went to a Nissan dealership who refused to allow me to charge. Salesman even reached to unplug my vehicle at Nissan after standing there watching me plug up. The charging station was new at Nissan and he just wanted to see if it worked. I'm nobody's guinea pig. JERK!$0.30/kwhr for the first two hours.   Nice safe spot.They're not opened 24 hours it matches the dealers closing time

column9: 9037 Pearl Rd, Strongsville, OH 44136, USA
column13: Stalls are in the rear of the main entrance.  It was empty when we got here. Within 5 minutes we had a few vehicles.  Then an F150 pulled up and I thought we were about to be ICE'd. Turns out it was Tesla Energy stopping to check on something.  No problems charging at 95 kW for us.  It was easy to find off the exit.A good spot to stop and charge before heading across the rest of the Ohio Turnpike. Plenty of spots to charge at night......when we were here during the day there was a small queue due to options for charging being limited in parts of the state.  A few minutes down the road are some good spots to eat if you are looking for vegan or vegetarian options - we highly recommend Aladdin's!Good location for charging located in the back lot of a well-equipped Sheetz convenience store with decent restrooms. We bought some grab-n-go salads, after rude service at nearby O'Charley's. Spaces are back in. It was a little busy for a Tuesday night but we managed.Very busy when I visited. Still fast charging. Located in a convenience store parking lot which is great.Excellent location next to Sheetz (

column9: 2309 Ross Clark Cir, Dothan, AL 36301, USA
column13: I came by here at 1:00am needing a boost, but found the charger marked "UNAVAILABLE."  But today I called the Mercedes dealership and the receptionist said it was available to the public 24 hours and was currently marked "AVAILABLE."  Also, according to the ChargePoint agent I spoke with, "UNAVAILABLE" usually means the station is not connected to the Internet preventing it from working with the app, but it should continue to work with the ChargePoint credit card or, possibly, any credit card.

column9: 947 W St Marys St, Centerville, TX 75833, USA
column13: Behind the Collin Street Bakery. Had to wait approximately 15 minutes for a charger to open. 1/2 the cars did not have people in them. It always makes you wonder how long and how many of those cars are fully charged but just idling. Yeah idling fees don‚Äôt help me get on the road though. Charged up to 80% and continued on my trip from DFW area to Houston round trip. Y‚Äôall be Safe out there.Good and spacious place. There is a Woodrow's BBQ place that also sells random things you would see at Buccee's. Clean restrooms. There is also a subway in that plaza as well. Good stop between Houston and Dallas.8/21 update:  looks like Tesla realized this location needs more bandwidth and is adding 8 more stalls. Changed to 5 stars.  Great location, pretty much in the middle between Houston and Dallas.  This allows me to skip the absolute horrible Supercharger location in Huntsville.  Woody‚Äôs is a short walk away for refreshments and restroom.  Minus 1 star for being only 4 stalls as this is getting to be a very busy charging stop.  Hopefully Tesla installs more stalls here in the near future.Less star because it was so hard to find there was thin lane between highway and gas station and I missed it and went on highway by mistake and it took 20 more miles for next exit to come back to this supercharger!!! No restroom at least within 2-3 mins distance.Behind Woody's smokehouse in the corner of the parking lot. Just in case a semi is blocking the view. We went over to the chevron which wa open late at night.

column9: Lassiter at North Hills Ave, Raleigh, NC 27609, USA
column13: A really super supercharging station. 12, 250kW and 12, 150kW Superchargers. A good spot to get a bite to eat. In a busy shopping center parking lot. Great selection and wide variety of shops and restaurants within walking distance.There are plenty of stalls very clean and well lit area right beside the target.  My issue is the price is going up! It used to be 19 cents per kilowatt off peak and then 30 cents on peak but now is 25 cents off peak and $0.30 on peak! They also pushed the times back to 8:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. for on peak!  The off-peak times used to be up to 11:00. A.m.Importantly, this place has both 150KWH and 250KWH charger (12 each). It was nice trip to the charger. I was expecting delays or slow due to the busy nature of the area but I still got one solo on 150K charger. For my model 3, from 12% to 8% in less than 30 minutes, no complains here. Target and Starbucks on two minutes walk, tempting but I resisted. Well lit and clean,  Overall a good experience. Noisy, I must say but that is because I-440 is just right behind the fence. Fortunately or Unfortunately, this is the only one in Raleigh City limits.There are 12 150kw superchargers and several 250kw superchargers, plus other EV chargers.  Love that the superchargers are parallel to your car when parking (versus perpendicular). Watch for the other people driving very fast on this road.This is a big Supercharger in a busy area but we were able to get 254kW even with 12 of the available stalls taken.

column13: For a traveler, there isn't anything else here, except a nice mountain view and the DCFC. The fast charge is great and there are plenty of fast chargers, as well as L2 chargers. No restroom. You'll want your car sunshades. For the employees of Jaguar Land, this must be fantastic. You can plug in a J1772 while you're at work. Or use the CCS or CHAdeMO for a quick "fill-up" anytime during the day.Thank you for creating this massive amount of chargers however what is up with the pricing structure?! I used the Level-3 Quick Charge (CCS/SAE Combo) for 5 minutes and only received 2kWh at 40¬¢ per minute!? That would be on the very high side per kWh which is what I thought it must surely be. Nope, per minute. I was charging an e-Golf and only charged at 24-25kW which is extremely low for a Level-3. Please be competitive with Electrify America, EVgo and other ChargePoint stations. I often pay zero, but this is extremely high. I didn't check the cost of the Level-2 as I was very low and didn't want to even entertain waiting here for a few hours. Please revise pricing per kWh and I'll gladly come back as well as update this review. I wound up charging at an Electrify America at the speed of around 50kW (still slow for level-3) at a very high 43¬¢ per kWh with no subscription.Great fast new chargers but ONLY for Jaguar employees.Great EV Charging, fast, it's in the jaguar range Rover parking lot, lots of chargers, plus slow chargers as well. Open to the public, no you do not need an account, you can just tap your credit card and start
